Subject: gate OMPL's vendored nanobind on OMPL_BUILD_PYTHON_BINDINGS

OMPL's CMakeModules/OMPLDependencies.cmake unconditionally
add_subdirectory()s its own vendored nanobind (sub-sub-submodule) as
soon as it sees the file on disk and finds a Python interpreter,
without checking OMPL_BUILD_PYTHON_BINDINGS.  The vendored nanobind
2.x then runs its own CMake which hard-errors on Python < 3.9 — making
cp38 wheel builds impossible even when the consumer (us) has
explicitly set OMPL_BUILD_PYTHON_BINDINGS=OFF and never wanted the
vendored nanobind in the first place.

This patch adds the missing OMPL_BUILD_PYTHON_BINDINGS gate so the
add_subdirectory only runs when OMPL is actually going to build its
own Python bindings.  When (eventually) OMPL accepts this fix
upstream, this patch becomes a no-op and can be deleted.

--- a/CMakeModules/OMPLDependencies.cmake
+++ b/CMakeModules/OMPLDependencies.cmake
@@ -92,7 +92,7 @@ set_package_properties(Nanobind PROPERTIES
     URL "https://github.com/wjakob/nanobind"
     PURPOSE "Used for building Python bindings.")

-if(OMPL_HAVE_PYTHON AND EXISTS "${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/external/nanobind/CMakeLists.txt")
+if(OMPL_BUILD_PYTHON_BINDINGS AND OMPL_HAVE_PYTHON AND EXISTS "${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/external/nanobind/CMakeLists.txt")
     add_subdirectory(${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/external/nanobind)
     set(OMPL_HAVE_NANOBIND 1)
 else()
